The University of Macau today (27) held the “Second Macao Stem Cell Seminar ”, which attracts more than one hundred experts and scholars from the United States, Singapore, Mainland, Hong Kong and Macao, and experts and scholars engaged in“ extra-stem stem cell ” research, and share and discuss the latest technological developments and development of stem cell research with teachers and students of Macao universities.
Vice-Chancellor (Research) Ge Wei said that stem cell research is of medical value and is also one of the key scientific research projects of the University of Australia, which will help promote Macao's research and development in the field of stem cells.
Ge Wei said that as a leading international comprehensive university on the west bank of the Guangdong-Hong Kong-Macao Greater Bay Area, Australia is committed to building a talent training base and science and technology innovation center for the West Coast of the Greater Bay Area, helping the innovation and development of the Bay Area.
The seminar brought together stem cell experts at home and abroad to share the latest technology, which will help promote the research and development of stem cells in Macao.
Deng Yuxia, president of the Australian University School of Health Sciences, said that in recent years, Australia has continuously strengthened scientific research and innovation and transformation, and has also improved the number and quality of papers, and the University has also achieved fruitful results in stem cell research.
At the meeting, a group of well-known scholars shared cutting-edge knowledge and cutting-edge technology of stem cell research.
Ji Weizhi, a member of the Chinese Academy of Sciences and dean of the School of primate translation at Kunming University of Science and Technology, Yunnan, explained the process of using the 3D culture system to study monkeys and human embryos in vibe and their molecular mechanisms; Jing Naihe, a researcher at the Shanghai Institute of Biochemical Cells of the Chinese Academy of Sciences, expounded the spatial and temporal changes in the cell spectrum after the implantation of mouse embryos from single-cells and molecular levels; and Wang Yong, a professor at Penn State University, showed you how to use biomaterial hydrogels to simulate stem cell micrones for survival and transportation.
Xu Ren, Vice President (Research) of the Australian University of Health Sciences (research), Assistant President Chen Guokai and Associate Professor Wang Chunming of the Australasian Chinese Medicine Research Institute, also introduced the important results of his latest release.
The "Second Macao Stem Cell Seminar" was organized by the School of Health Sciences of the University of Macau, co-organized by the Chinese Medicine Research Institute of the University of Macau and the National Key Laboratory of Chinese Quality Research of the University of Science and Technology of Macao, and attended by Chen Ling'an, Acting Senior Manager of the Macao Science and Technology Development Fund.
The seminar featured 11 academic reports on embryonic development and tissue generation, translational medicine, research and translational applications of stem cells, biomaterials and applications.
The atmosphere of the seminar was a warm atmosphere, and the participants actively discussed and shared the latest research and views on relevant technologies.
Xu Renhe said that the seminar provided a platform for communication and cooperation for stem cell experts in the Greater Bay Area and beyond, and also provided students with valuable learning opportunities.
