Chirac's death of political legacy
On the 26th local time, former French President Chirac died at the age of 86.
At a time when the world is in a century of great changes, the many political legacies left by this French politician when he came to power are still worthy of our praise.
Chirac has been the president of France for 12 years in a very personal charismatic fashion.
He has inherited both the spirit of de Gaulle's independence and independence, and his firm support for European integration, and is a representative figure chasing the "European dream."
At the same time, he also strongly advocated the world's multipolarization and multilateralism, and was a strategic politician.
That's why the French press rated him as "a distinguished representative of France on the world stage."
One of Chirac's relished political decisions was against the U.S.-led Iraq war.
Under his leadership, France and Germany have withstood the pressure of the United States and are at the forefront of the war.
A year after the war broke out, he predicted that the Iraq war would lead to increased terrorist activities and made the world more dangerous.
It later turned out that Chirac's warning was quite right.
At a time when European integration is in a turbulent way and the unilateralism of the United States is becoming more and more prominent, and Chirac is undoubtedly of great implications for strategic thinking and choices about international politics and global affairs.
Chirac is also a French politician who has made the Chinese feel familiar and affectionate.
He is one of the advocates and creators of the "Golden Decade" of China-France relations, and after his first election as the French president in 1995, he promoted the rapid development of China-France relations with the strategic vision of politicians.
In 2004, China and France established a comprehensive strategic partnership, and bilateral exchanges between China and France entered a new stage.
During the reign of Chirac, bilateral trade between China and France grew rapidly, and the two countries had made breakthroughs in cooperation in aviation, nuclear energy, railway transportation and other fields.
The Chirac's China-France Cultural Year, which created a new model of cultural exchange in the history of China and France.
Chirac ’ s lifelong love for Chinese culture is particularly impressive.
It is understood that his Chinese diplomats introduced that Chirac could back some of the poems of Li Bai and Du Fu, and even accurately judge the historical years of Chinese bronzes.
"Not to see the pyramids is not really to Egypt, do not see that the Qin figurines have really been to China" - this golden sentence comes from Chirac.
In an interview with Xinhua, Chirac said: “The West has concerns about China ’ s political and social development, the ecological issues arising from China ’ s economic growth, and China ’ s political status in the international arena.
But I have confidence in China.
I believe that China is a country with a long history of civilization, and its experience is enough to help it build the ideals and values for achieving harmonious development, and assume its responsibilities on the world stage for a long time. "
I also believe that China's renaissance will bring new creative vitality to the world's culture and enrich the world culture.
The Sman is gone, but the political legacy and revelations that Chirac has left for the world will last forever.
