On September 26th, local time, State Councilor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi presided over the meeting of foreign ministers of China and the Security Council of African member states at the United Nations Headquarters in New York.
The meeting was attended by the current African Security Council Foreign Minister Tano, Foreign Minister Oyono, Foreign Minister of Equatorial Guinea, Foreign Minister Pandor of South Africa and Foreign Minister Kara, Minister-General-elect of Niger, and Tunisian Foreign Minister Jessinawi.
Wang Yi put forward four suggestions on strengthening China-Africa cooperation in the Security Council.
First, by unity.
The biggest challenge in the current international situation is unilateralism, and the direct consequence is that the basic norms governing international relations are challenged, and the role of the United Nations has been affected, which has damaged the interests of developing countries and small and medium-sized countries, including African countries.
To meet this challenge, it is necessary for China and Africa to shoulder and shoulder to shoulder, so that unity can only be empowered.
In the Council, the three African countries speak with one voice, and the focus is not just three votes, but the entire African continent.
China and Africa stand together, not just 4 votes, but will lead other countries to follow suit, influence and shape the agenda of the Security Council.
Since 2018, China has established a "3+1" coordination mechanism with African members of the Security Council, which should be fully utilized.
Second, by consultation to solve disputes.
China has always advocated the political settlement of hot-button issues, has a good tradition of consultation in Africa, and has the experience of successful mediation by African regional and subregional organizations.
Many of the complex challenges on the Council ’ s agenda, in particular the African hotspots, are mostly the root causes of colonialism, and some are directly related to external factors.
We must make good use of Chapter VI of the Charter of the United Nations and play a good role in the role of the United Nations in good offices and mediation.
Third, self-reliance.
African countries and people know best about Africa's problems, and Africa has the ability and wisdom to solve its own problems.
The Security Council, dealing with hot-button issues in Africa, should focus on listening and respecting Africa's will, should play the role of regional and subregional organizations, and should encourage and support endogenous solutions from Africa.
China is willing to strengthen coordination with Africa and firmly promote capacity-building for Africa's autonomous peace operations.
Fourth, by development.
Both China and the vast number of African countries are developing countries. We must adhere to putting economic and social development first and supporting each other's chosen development path.
China is willing to jointly build the Belt and Road Initiative with the AU's Agenda 2063, the United Nations 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development, and the development strategies of African countries to help African countries enhance their development capabilities and eliminate the root causes of conflict.
We must jointly promote the United Nations to increase its investment in Africa.
China has made every effort to provide human and material assistance to the United States, and is willing to coordinate its actions with African countries to mobilize the United Nations and the World Health Organization to increase assistance and play the role of the United Nations Stabilization Mission in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC) and the United Nations Stabilization Mission in the Democratic Republic of the Congo.
