Make tea with plastic tea!
According to the Central News Agency, a recent Canadian study found that a packet of plastic tea bags may release billions or even tens of billions of plastic particles, which is significantly higher than the amount of microplastics estimated that a person's annual intake of microplastics is not available, but there is no evidence to show that ingesting plastic particles can pose a threat to humans.
According to reports, researchers at the University of Magill University in Canada found that immersion plastic tea bags into a cup of almost boiling hot water (Celebration 95 degrees Celsius), and the tea bag will release about 116 billion plastic particles and 31 billion smaller nanoplastics into cups.
This amount is significantly higher than the amount of microplastics an estimated amount of microplastics a person per year.
According to the research published earlier in 2019, people generally eat at least 50,000 microplastics a year and inhale the same amount of microplastics.
It is reported that the study was published in the Journal of Environmental Science and Technology, where researchers tested four different types of plastic commercial tea bags in the Montreal Store and Cafe, opened the tea bag, and immerged the tea bag in the almost boiling water for five minutes, and analyzed with electron microscopes and spectrometers.
According to the study, they found that a single tea bag released more than 116 billion plastic particles, "several years higher than the plastic load of previous foods."
Most of the tea bags are made of natural fibers, but many tea bags that use natural fibers are still used to seal the bottle.
Some branded tea bags no longer need paper to use plastic instead of plastic, and these plastic tea bags are the test subjects for researchers.
Plastic particles are tiny fragments of plastic, which the researchers define is between 100nm and between 100nm and 5cm, and is mainly produced by the breakdown of plastic waste.
Researchers have found traces of plastic particles in air, soil, rivers and the most deep-sea trenches around the world, and can also be found in running water, bottled water, seafood and beer.
In October 2018, the researchers first found microplastics in human stool samples in several countries in different regions of the world.
To test the potential toxicity of the tea bag release of microplastic particles, the Canadian team put fleas into contaminated water, finding that microplastics can affect the behavior of these fleas and allow them to develop deformities.
According to the World Health Organization (WHO), there is no evidence to date that ingesting plastic particles poses a threat to humans.
However, the WHO notes that more research is needed to fully understand how these plastics spread to the environment and what impact they have on humans.
The researchers speculated that the reason these tea bags release large amounts of plastic particles, which may be due to contacting boiling water in these plastic tea bags, which may break down or seep toxic substances even when "edible grade" plastic is heated to above 40 degrees Celsius.
