China Releases Report on China and the United Nations, and Issues on Climate Change, Sustainable Development - Xinhua
On September 26th, the Chinese delegation to the 74th session of the United Nations General Assembly officially released the "China and the United Nations - China's Position Paper on the 74th Session of the United Nations General Assembly", the United Nations Climate Action Summit: China's Position and Actions, the Progress Report on the Implementation of the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development (2019), and the Report on Earth Big Data Support Sustainable Development Goals.
The China and the United Nations Statement on China's Position Paper at the 74th Session of the United Nations General Assembly summarizes the achievements and development of China's cooperation with the United Nations in various fields in the 70 years since the founding of New China, especially since the 18th National Congress of the Communist Party of
It is pointed out that the proposal of Chinese President Xi Jinping to promote the construction of a community with a shared future for mankind has become the banner of major-country diplomacy with Chinese characteristics.
Under the guidance of Xi Jinping's diplomatic thinking, China has participated in international affairs with a more active and effective attitude, made greater contributions to world peace and development, and assumed more responsibilities.
China has always been a builder of world peace, a contributor to global development and a defender of the international order.
The document introduces China's important contributions to the three pillars of peace, development and human rights in the United Nations from ten aspects.
We reaffirm China's firm support and practice of multilateralism, and support the United Nations in playing a central role in international affairs; point out that China's development and the development of the world are the same frequency, and the two promote each other; and emphasize that in the face of the great changes that the world has not seen in a century, a growing China will contribute more and more positive energy to the world.
The UN Climate Action Summit: China's Position and Actions closely follows the nine major areas of action of the UN Climate Action Summit, and introduces China's policy proposition on international cooperation in addressing climate change and China's achievements in addressing climate change.
As the world's largest developing country, China regards addressing climate change as an inherent requirement for its sustainable development and its responsibility for building a community with a shared future for mankind. It will continue to overcome many of the difficult challenges facing its own development, firmly uphold multilateralism, implement international commitments, and make every effort to promote the full and effective implementation of the Paris Agreement.
Progress Report on China's Implementation of the Agenda for Sustainable Development (2019) for China's implementation of the 2030 Agenda for Sustainable Development is the second progress report issued by China following the release of the progress report on its implementation in 2017.
The report comprehensively sorted out China's initiatives, progress, challenges and next steps to implement the 2020 Agenda, and demonstrated China's determination and achievements in implementing the new development concept and achieving high-quality development.
The cases of precision poverty alleviation, innovation-led development, ecological civilization construction, rural revitalization, and joint construction of the "Belt and Road" include the report will provide useful reference for other countries to implement the 2030 Agenda.
The Earth Big Data Supports Sustainable Development Goals Report showcases China's exploration and practice of using Earth big data to support the implementation of the 2030 Agenda, reveals the value and prospects of relevant technologies and methods for monitoring and evaluating the application of sustainable development goals, and provides new perspectives and new support for the international community to fill the gaps in data and methodology and accelerate the implementation of the 2030 Agenda.
