According to the Central News Agency, on the 26th local time, U.S. health officials said that 12 people have died from e-cigarette-related diseases in the United States, while there have been 805 cases of lung damage related to vaping.
The U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has reportedly reported the figures and said it has not yet identified specific substances that cause the disease.
However, most patients have reported that e-cigarette products containing tetrahydrocannabinol containrole have been used, which is the main compound in which cannabis can affect mental state.
It is reported that the surge in lung cases has been linked to the purchase of contaminated electronic smoke agents in the black market.
The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention pointed out that the above 12 deaths occurred in 10 states from California to Florida, and the number of confirmed and suspected cases related to the 805 were reported by 46 states and the US Virgin Islands.
In the past three weeks, the sale of e-cigarettes has been banned in India and the United States, while the state of Michigan and Michigan have banned flavored e-cigarettes.
The Trump administration intends to ban all flavored e-cigarette products other than tobacco flavors from October.
