The Fair Work Commission found that the owner of a Foodworks supermarket fired an 66-year-old female worker by text message because he was more willing to hire an employee from an Asian background, and the boss's approach was slammed as "shameful."
The committee said that the way Ms. Gail Ayton, who has worked at the Wagga Wagga store for more than 20 years, is "extremely unfair" in the way that Eddie treats employees and may have violated anti-discrimination laws.
Ms Ayton told the committee that Mr Wang took over the store in 2016 and that he had always "wanted to fire me" because she wasn't Chinese.
In this case, the vice chairman of the committee, Peter Sams, conducted a search on the Internet and found that "some of the job advertisements that Mr. Wang has published in the past at various Chinese-Australian employment forums."
Among the job requirements listed in these positions, one of the said "Preferred Asian ladies" and the other said "Preferred Asian employees"
The third post says he "fisted more attractive to overseas people (the original)"
Mr Wang fired Ms. Ayton by text message in April this year, which he later said was due to her absence and the alleged drop in cash from $5.10 to $30 for the cash register.
But Mr Sams said the reason for Mr Wang's dismissal of Ms. Ayyton was weak and there was also a lack of evidence.
In the past three years, she has only been absent from one shift, and the “missing amount ” totals a few Australian dollars.
He said Ms Ayton's dismissal "actually had nothing to do with her behaviour or performance."
He said: "In my opinion, with the evidence of the job adverts posted by Mr Wang, the real motivation for the defense to fire her was that he was more willing to hire an employee with an Asian background.
Under section 7772 (f) of the Fair Work Act, Mr. Wang's conduct ostensibly constitutes an unlawful violation of the Anti-Discrimination Act and / or dismissal of an applicant. ”
Mr Sams said that in view of Mr Wang's "apprompral treatment" to Ms Ayyton, it would not be appropriate for him to consider resuming her position.
He should consider paying compensation to Ms Ayton, who is a temporary worker with a salary of $26 at the time.
In light of possible violations of anti-discrimination and industrial relations legislation, Sams said he would submit his rulings and documents to the head of the committee to consider whether Mr. Wang's conduct should be referred to other agencies to investigate possible violations of state or federal law.
He said Mr Wang had not given Ms Ayton any chance to respond to the reasons allegedly for dismissing her.
“I believe that the defence should have taken an incorrigible injustice and biased procedure to dismiss the applicant, and Mr. Wang ’ s “wait ” for this opportunity, which he believes would be ‘ proof ’ of being justified in termiophagement of employment to the applicant, ” he said.
"He was wrong... the respondent completely ignored any natural and just treatment accorded to her when he dismissed the applicant, and it was shocking that he was perfunctory and extremely unfair."
Mr. Sams said that while Foodworks was a small business, “it must be frank that any decent employer will not fire employees in a very unfair and perfunctory manner that is acknowledged in this case. ”
He said, “It ’ s shameful, and it ’ s extremely unfair. ”
