China is expected to be Australia ’ s largest beef export market.
A Dutch co-organisation analyst at Rabobank said China faced a severe pork shortage after the outbreak of African swine fever, which is expected to be Australia's largest beef export market.
After the outbreak, Chinese consumers are shifting from edible pork to other animal proteins, which has allowed authorities to destroy many herds. In the past year, China's hogs have halved and pork prices nearly doubled.
China produces and consumes two-thirds of the world's pork.
Chenjun Pan, a senior animal protein analyst at the Bank of China of the Dutch Bank, said that the demand for other meats, including beef, has increased, with China, the world's largest importer of animal protein, now accounting for 27% of the world's pork imports and 24 percent of the world's beef imports.
Ms Pan said that in the first half of this year, China's imports of beef from Australia increased by 65 percent, and China overtook the US and Japan to become Australia's largest beef export market.
Yesterday, the Chinese government said it would release more pork from the emergency reserve ahead of the 70th anniversary of the Chinese Communist Party's rule.
