French finance minister says it will cut taxes more than ten billion euros next year and calls on Germany to follow suit
PARIS (Reuters) - French Finance Minister Bruno Le Maire said on Thursday that France would cut taxes by more than 100bn euros ($109 billion) next year, while Germany should keep pace with France's fiscal stimulus to revive the sluggish economy.
Introducing France's 2020 budget, Le Maire said the ECB's latest monetary easing has created an opportunity to increase investment for those able member governments.
The European Central Bank cut interest rates to a record low on September 12 and plans to restart bond purchases to depress borrowing costs in hopes of incentivizing the recovery and pushing up inflation.
“Low interest rates will not allow Europe to prosper, and monetary policy measures are necessary but not enough, ” Le Maire told reporters.
"Germany needs to invest, and it needs it now, the sooner the better. Don't wait until the situation is worse and then act," he added.
He has made this appeal to Germany on several occasions.
France has already implemented tax cuts of more than €100bn this year, giving a big boost to France's economic growth.
And the global economy lost momentum, and the export-dependent German economy bore the brunt.
Le Maire noted that the tax burden on French households will be reduced by €93bn next year, including €5bn in income tax relief.
In addition, the corporate tax burden will be reduced by nearly €1bn as the corporate tax rate is gradually implemented from 33.3% to 25% over the five-year period.
