Study: U.S. National Healthy Eating Index Grows Smallly, Still a Challenge
According to the U.S. Overseas Chinese News Network, a recent study shows that in the past 16 years, the U.S. government's healthy eating index has grown moderately, growing from 56 to 58.
But in the case where the full score is 100 points, it's not worth celebrating.
American nationals still face “significant challenges ” in their diet.
Dr. Zhang Fangfang, one of the study's authors and a nutrition researcher at Tufts University in Massachusetts, said that Americans still consume too much food that may cause diseases such as heart disease, diabetes, and obesity, which are the most common diseases of the United States.
The study was published in the Journal of the American Medical Association on the 24th.
The study was based on the conclusions of the U.S. government's health survey of 4.4 million adults conducted between 1999 and 2016.
The authors write, "Despite considerable improvements, significant dietary challenges remain."
These challenges include reducing the intake of snacks, hot dogs, fat cows, butter and other foods containing saturated fat.
The study found that people's daily intake of these unhealthy fats increased from 11.5% to 12%, exceeding the recommended 10% intake.
The biggest improvement in the U.S. diet is that the sugar intake has been reduced from 16 percent to about 14 percent, but the intake is still too high.
Officials believe that the daily diet of added sugar intake should be less than 10%.
For the reasons for the decrease in sugar intake, the researchers believe that people are related to the reduction of sweet soda, but Zhang Fangfang stressed that sugar is often added to even sweet foods, such as yogurt and ketchup.
U.S. adults have increased slightly in their intake of fruits, nuts, oats, and other whole grain categories.
However, data from 2016 show that these foods still account for less than five percent of their daily diets.
Although people's slightly less salt intake, and the reduction in drinking fruit juices has led to low-quality carbohydrate intake, Zhang Fangfang said they still account for up to 42 percent of daily calories, many of which come from refined white-sided bread and other refined grains.
The study, based on a biennial personal health survey, would allow adults to recall the food they ate in the last 24 hours.
These health surveys have been asking the issue twice every few days since 2003.
The U.S. Department of Dietary Guidelines for U.S. Residents advises people to adopt a "healthy eating model" to reduce the likelihood of developing a chronic disease.
The guidelines point out that people should eat more nutritious foods, such as vegetables, fruits, whole grains, low-fat dairy products, and the seafood, lean meat, poultry meat, eggs, and seed foods that can provide protein.
During the survey, the number of people with diabetes among U.S. nationals nearly doubled, more than 7%, and the obesity rate increased in many years of the survey, and about 70% of American adults are overweight or obese.
In addition, heart disease remains the leading cause of death among U.S. nationals.
