Economic and trade frictions affect the "report card" of the US economy.
The U.S. economic "tran note" for the second quarter of this year showed that the growth rate of U.S. gross domestic product (GDP) slowed significantly compared with the previous quarter due to the sharp decline in private sector investment and exports.
Analysts pointed out that economic and trade frictions and the uncertainty it brought about is the main reason for the decline in private sector investment and exports in the second quarter.
The final revised data released by the US Department of Commerce on the 26th showed that U.S. GDP grew at an annual rate of 2% in the second quarter, which was the same as the previously announced revised data, but significantly lower than the 3.1% in the first quarter.
The data show that consumption growth became a major factor underpinning U.S. economic growth in the second quarter.
Personal consumption expenditure, which accounts for about 70% of the total U.S. economy, increased by 4.6% in the quarter, driving economic growth by 3.03 percentage points.
In addition, government consumption spending and investment drive economic growth by 0.82 percentage points.
However, private sector investment fell 6.3% in the second quarter from the previous quarter, dragging down 1.16 percentage points of economic growth in the quarter; exports fell 5.7% from the previous quarter, and net exports dragged down the quarter's economic growth by 0.68 percentage points.
Barry Knapp, managing partner of the U.S.-based Aynside Macroeconomics Consulting, said that private-sector investment has not only failed to maintain last year's growth momentum, but has fallen sharply, because economic and trade frictions and rising uncertainty have hit corporate confidence.
Knapp believes that under the influence of policy uncertainty, U.S. corporate capital spending is expected to remain in a downward trend next year.
Analysts believe that although consumption growth strongly supported the U.S. economy in the second quarter, there are growing signs that economic and trade frictions and the uncertainty it brings about affect consumer confidence and adversely affect the U.S. consumption outlook.
Richard Curtin, head of the survey and a professor of economics at the University of Michigan, said that in the most recent survey, 38% of consumers spontaneously mentioned the negative impact of tariffs on the U.S. economy, which is a new high in a year and a half.
For the future of the U.S. economy, analysts generally believe that the U.S. economy will continue to slow down
But some experts said that if the economic and trade frictions are eased, the performance of the US industrial sector and financial markets will improve.
Kailyn Birch, a global economist at the British Economist think tank, expects that the U.S. economy will continue the gradual decline trend this year in the future, and the growth rate will fall to a lower level than in the second quarter.
Mark Zandi, chief economist at Moody ’ s Analytics, predicts that the U.S. economy ’ s growth will be 2.3% this year, and it will slow to 1.6% next year, assuming that economic and trade frictions will not continue to escalate.
Ellen Hatyn pointed out that the biggest concern of enterprises at present is the economic and trade disputes and the uncertainty it brings, and if the economic and trade disputes can be resolved, the uncertainty will be greatly reduced, and the performance of the industrial sector will be much better than it is now.
Matt Meli, equity strategist at Miller-Tabak Asset Management, said that economic and trade frictions are still the "top number one problem" and the main reason for the large fluctuations in the US capital market this year, and whether economic and trade frictions can be properly resolved will be the key to affecting the direction of the US capital market for the rest of the year.
