After a marathon debate and weeks of protests, on September 26, local time, the Australian state passed the abortion legalization bill in New Australia.
It is reported that the bill has sparked political debate in the past eight weeks, and there have been serious divisions within the Australian Liberal Party since independent MP Greenwich announced the introduction of the bill.
After nearly 40 hours of discussion, the ANZ Senate passed the abortion legalization bill by a vote of 26 to 14 on the evening of the 25th, making it the third-longest bill for the NSW Senate to consider it.
On the morning of the 26th, after the final vote was held in the NSW House, which legalized abortion in NSW.
The bill allows women to terminate their pregnancies at 22 weeks of pregnancy and, if two doctors agree, also allow a woman to have an abortion later in pregnancy.
The Senate passed an amendment on the evening of the 25th, in which doctors can seek advice from the hospital's advisory committee on multidisciplinary team before performing abortions for a woman 22 weeks after pregnancy.
In addition, the Senate-passed amendment includes that doctors must provide appropriate care for babies who survive after terminating pregnancy.
Previously, NSW Premier Berry Gikle had faced public criticism from conservatives on the bill, and Berrejeklian stepped in on several occasions to secure more debate time for the bill, but she did not attend the final vote.
Berrejeklian defended his absence vote, saying, "I need to take the time to manage the whole of NSW."
It is reported that Liberal MP Davis, a former strongest opponent of the abortion bill, has threatened to withdraw from the NSW government, saying the bill has triggered a "government crisis."
But then Davis made concessions.
“The contents of the amendments to the abortion law enforcement bill submitted to the House on the morning of the 26th actually provide more security for women and doctors, ” Davis said.
Meanwhile, Australia's NSW National Party leader Barillaro says he is proud to be a part of a government that legalizes abortion.
“Our achievements last night were historic in the new state, which legalized abortion, and abortion is no longer a criminal act, and it will not treat abortion women as criminals. ”
