Iran has been confirmed to develop advanced centrifuges to further suspend implementation of Iran nuclear agreement
According to the Central News Agency, the United Nations International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) said on the 26th that Iran's use of advanced centrifuges to make enriched uranium has once again violated the Iranian nuclear agreement.
According to reports, Iran is gradually violating the restrictions of the Iran nuclear agreement in response to US President Donald Trump's withdrawal from the Iran nuclear agreement in May 2018, and the resumption and strengthening of sanctions against Iran.
Iran has suspended two other commitments in July to keep the stockpile of enriched uranium below 300kg, and the purity of enriched uranium does not exceed 3.67 percent, and there are now further moves.
According to the nuclear agreement, Iran can only set up about 5000 first-generation IR-1 centrifuges in Natanz to accumulate enriched uranium, and only allows Iran to use a small number of more advanced models for research, but does not produce enriched uranium.
If Iran succeeds in developing more advanced centrifuges, it will be able to produce enriched uranium at a rate several times faster, possibly for the use of nuclear bombs.
According to the report, the International Atomic Energy Agency report said: "On September 25th, the Agency confirmed that the advanced centrifuges of the two, the model of the model 3 in Iran... are accumulating or preparing to accumulate enriched uranium."
The United Nations International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) presented the report to Member States on the 26th, and a diplomatic official responded: “They are busy at the [Nutriun enriched uranium] facility. ”
